  title={Poster Abstract: Towards Shapley Value based Security Risk Attribution in Sensor Networks}, 
  year={2022},
  volume={},
  number={},
  pages={519-520},
  abstract={Sensor Networks (SNs) are comprised of low-cost nodes deployed in an ad-hoc fashion over a large area and thus are susceptible to various security attacks. Overall SN's security metrics are often modeled by stochastic or Bayesian Attack Graphs which assume certain likelihoods of feasible attacks paths. This paper discusses a next step, security risk attribution to individual SN's components/vulnerabilities, which is an integral part of efficient risk miti-gation. The challenges are due to highly non-linear contribution of individual vulnerabilities to the overall system security risk and as-tronomically large number of mitigation scenarios in real systems. Motivated by (a) uniqueness of Shapley-value based attribution having some desirable properties, and (b) successful application of this attribution in various settings including financial risk attribution, we propose a Shapley value-based security risk attribution to individual SN's components/vulnerabilities.},
  keywords={Measurement;Stochastic processes;Information processing;Ad hoc networks;Bayes methods;Security;sensor networks;security risk;Shapley value-based risk attribution},
